Lets use data digits dataset provided in python library, sklearn

    %matplotlib inline
    from sklearn.datasets import load_digits
    from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
    import numpy as np
    
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    
    digits_data = load_digits()
    
    digits = digits_data.data
    targets = digits_data.target
    
    digits.shape
    targets.shape
    
    
    >>> (1797,)

Lets plot a input and see how it looks

    a_digit = np.split(digits[0], 8)
    plt.imshow(a_digit, cmap='gray')

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Now that we have seen the digit.

Lets split data in to training and test data for validation purpose

    # SPLIT training data and test data
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(digits, targets, test_size=0.25)
    print x_train.shape, x_test.shape
    
    
    >>> (1347, 64) (450, 64)

Now lets start LogisticRegression and train(fit) using training dataset

    from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
    
    logistic_reg = LogisticRegression()
    logistic_reg.fit(x_train, y_train)

using the trained model lets predict the digit using a test input x_test\[4\]

    predict_data = x_test[4].reshape(1, -1)
    logistic_reg.predict(x_test[4].reshape(1, -1))

Whats the predicted data ?

    >>> array([3])

Lets print the input and validate

    plt.imshow(np.split(x_test[4], 8), cmap='gray')

![](data:image/png;base64,)  
Worked well, now try few more test data

    predict_data = x_test[17].reshape(1, -1)
    plt.imshow(np.split(x_test[17], 8), cmap='gray')
    logistic_reg.predict(x_test[17].reshape(1, -1))
    
    
    >>> array([5])
